video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text: The best advice on how to think about life was that you don't have to become someone, you already are someone. Every second means change. Use the next one to change the way you want to. Find out what you are good at and what you love to do. If you don't know what that is, focus on what you can start doing without a cognitive barrier. As Robert said and experienced, it's always something that has to do with something you've always wanted to be. E.g. if you want to be a musician but you also want to be an actor and you've done one of them successfully but it hasn't really been the breakthrough yet, then try something that combines the two. If you are afraid of speaking in front of people, you can face the fear and learn it or you can do another part of the profession, e.g. screenwriting... If you start now and wake up in the next few weeks and keep working on this project with joy, then you are on a good path. There will be a sign (person, event...) along the way that looks like a great opportunity related to this path. It will only show up when you start to make your move.

comment_text:
“The early season of life” (34:10): Love what Steven has to say about concentration of investments (ex. skill-building, time, attention) to build up resources. I’m nothing like an economist. But since elementary school math, the concept of compound interest has enchanted me. This idea that doing hard stuff early on will continue to add benefits through time.

FTR, the “early season” does not have to be your 20s. Not all of us get that chance at that time. In my early 20s, I unexpectedly ended up being the caregiver^ to sick family members. It ended my career and derailed my plans for over a decade. I regret the lost time, but not the choice. The same rules of mastery apply.

^There’s not much awareness or research on unpaid family caregivers, but that’s changing as the Baby Boomers start to rely on them. One article, February 2025 from ABC News, states that there are 48 million UFCs in the U.S. (1 in 5 of American adults), and the cost would be $600B if they had to be paid.

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text:
1:33  so here’s **my feedback**:   Ok, I understand the desire to increase your subscriber numbers, but I think it’s important to recognize that having a healthy ratio of new viewers to subscribers is part of the natural growth process. When a channel is expanding, there will naturally be a good percentage of viewers who haven’t subscribed yet. Focusing too heavily on that conversion rate might unintentionally suggest that your goal is more about numbers than about building genuine engagement and growth. The right subscribers should come as people connect with the content over time.

I am not trying to be critical, I have just been seeing this opening statement from you and others more & more with large channels.    I don’t know if this is something social media management companies are pushing creators to say or whatever, but I just think this way of framing it can come across as manipulative and it doesn’t seem to reflect the actual thing most genuine creators are hoping to achieve with their content & channels over time.

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text:
Very interesting conversation. A lot of things said here made sense to me. However, I want to address two categories of things that Robert said, which I think are wrong or at best I don't agree with:

1. He said that people should be wary/suspicious of simple solutions and people peddling them. Quite frankly, I wonder if Mr. Greene prefers people who peddle complex solutions that make no sense, that people cannot relate to. I wonder if Mr. Greene values an idea or a solution only when it is complex. Will you trash an idea simply because it is simple, clear and straightforward?

Take for instance. Today one of the simplest ways of maintaining your health and avoiding diseases is "simply" by washing your hands. When this idea was first propounded almost two centuries ago, it seemed so simple and ridiculous. The man who proposed it was labeled mad and thrown into a lunatic asylum. Fast forward to the modern era, we know that this man was as correct as correct can be.

In short, people devalue a lot of things not because they are bad or wrong but simply because it looks so simple and easy, and people like to believe that things must be complex, difficult, stressful...before they are worthwhile or before any meaningful result can be earned. This mental framework seems wrong to me.

Don't forget that Mr. Greene has written several books, most of which I have read, like the 48 laws of power, Mastery, Laws of Human Nature...these books are essentially manuals for attaining power, mastery, and understanding people. Given how Mr. Greene broke down all these complex subjects into well-defined laws and steps, should we be wary and suspicious of them as well as Mr. Greene himself?

2. He also talks about how social media is ruining people's lives...he even goes as far as to name "Mark Zuckerberg" as knowing all the algorithms to use in hooking people.

Firstly, I want to ask. Do you have a personal beef with Mr. Mark? He is not the only owner of an online social media platform...

Secondly, Mr. Mark created products that people find easy and enjoyable to use. People use his products to connect with their loved ones, to hold business conversations, to form groups/communities about topics that they care about. People even use his platforms for their daily business operations.

If some people are using his products in a way that is harmful to them, is he supposed to apologize for that? Even something as helpful and life essential as food, people harm themselves by overeating...whose fault is that? Is it God/nature or is it the person that is overeating?

Should Mark Zuckerberg have created a useless platform that people find irritating?

Anyway, I am a fan of your books, but I was less than impressed with some aspects of this conversation. I think that you are biased because of some things and people that you don't like, such as social media, Mark Zuckerberg, and Donald Trump.

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text:
Great content, thanks! The only thing I disagree with is the idea of controlling emotions. We don’t actually control them—we learn to suppress them effectively. However, suppressed emotions don’t disappear; they build up and can wreak havoc within us until we recognize that emotions are not obstacles to be conquered, but rather context-intelligent information emerging from our experiences.

The level of emotional reactivity we experience reveals the current state of our relationship with that emotion and the aspects of life it is fused with. If we repress emotions, we only postpone the process of improving that relationship. Instead, we need to learn to normalize emotions, giving them the space to exist in our lives rather than resisting them. When we do this, the relationship improves naturally, and suppression is no longer necessary. Emotions arise, move through us, and, if not repressed, typically pass within about 30 seconds. Learning to flow with them rather than fight against them. That’s just my perspective based on my understanding and experience, curious to hear how others see it.

We don't like "different", we don't like "the other". I have no patience for superstitious, uneducated, simple people or those who do not understand what freedom or democracy mean. I don't admire them. I don't want to live with them. I don't want them voting in U.S. elections. Letting russians into the country was the biggest mistake of the 20th century. If being a Pollyanna is how Mr. Greene copes, I understand that. But it's not reality.

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text:
At 21 travelled to Egypt for 5 weeks, this before the Internet, so no communication with back home. It was tough, sand storms, mosquitoes, fear and extreme uncomfortable-ness. But the complete peace of mind and quietude that followed, because of that cathartic experience was incredibly profound. Then more travelling throughout my 20's searching for that same illusive peace, doing odd jobs to finance myself. Then chronic fatigue struck me down for an entire year, and THAT'S when I started to seriously do music. 10 years later and 100 songs written and recorded, I realised I had "failed". Then went into screenwriting and that's now starting to blossom.
If you don't know what to do, do what you think you want to do, and eventually you will land up doing what you're meant to be doing. And if nothing financial comes of it, you've spent your whole life doing what you loved.
Which is more than I can say for 90% of the planet.
author: @keithnelson9121

comment_text:
1) I don't know how we can put the expectation of knowing life's purpose and what one wants to do with the rest of one's life on 20 year olds and then wonder why they struggle to make the right decision.

2) IWe must  stop underestimating just how important of decision is being made when we choose a significant other.  The potential consequences to our emotional, spiritual, and psychological well being may be irreversible.  The amount of time, perhaps our most precious resource, and money invested in dating and on the engagement (ring!) and wedding/honeymoon, of which a six figure pricetag is not uncommon, is enormous.

This is not to mention buying a home together and, of course, the ultimate commitment and sacrifice, which is having children.  The amount of time, energy, and money this demands cannot be overrated.

The point I'm getting at is that our formal education curriculum offers literally zero subject matter whatsoever to help prepare us to make a decision the vast majority of people will be faced with at least once in their life, yet we sit and scratch our heads wondering why the divorce rate is so high.  No mystery here.

comment_text: "skills" talk around 20:00 is such bullshit. I don't pay anyone for skills. I only pay people when they have monopolies that force me to pay them for things I need or want. Like, I don't pay people very much for groceries. To the degree I pay, it's because Albertson's and Kroger are a duopoly in the US. I don't pay people for housing, except that land is a monopoly, so I have to. It's not a skill to own Albertson's or Kroger. It's not a skill to own land. Those are the big things I pay other people for, and it's almost entirely not by choice. I'm pretty typical of Americans. The typical American pays 30% of their money to housing, and 10% on food. I pay less to waiters and kitchen staff to cook and clean up after me, because I don't eat out. But, I can't avoid the duopoly of grocers, nor the monopoly of land.

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text:
Well, there is nuance to the concepts presented here. I agree that we are social animals that put structures in place and have a “power” game, but power isn’t always everything. Mr. Greene seems to be influenced by Adler and I have read Adler’s books as a young student trying to figure out why the world works the way it does and why do I myself feel the way I feel. I have social anxiety even now in my 30s and while trying to understand, I realised that even socially anxious or avoidant people are very self-focused just like narcissists (but with different presentations) and I thought- that’s interesting. I also realised that even people I admire that seemed to have the “appropriate” amount of humbleness - they have self-awareness, they have an image they present that they care about and are aware of (so they still self focus). I think the key is that self focus shouldn’t be the only thing one person focuses in a structural society such as ours…there needs to be some balance between the individual and the collective. I self isolate a lot and I am trying to learn to open up more, even with the risk of getting hurt. I think the conversation regarding: not to build fortresses surprised and touch me the most and I will meditate upon that. 

Interesting podcast. Congratulations!

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text: When I was five years old, I remember lying on my dad's bed and looking up at the ceiling thinking to myself, I'm five years old, I wonder how many  five years will I experience, five year increments, before I die.  In my high school yearbook I wrote my goal in life was to experience peace of mind. Now I'm 62 and by all worldly measures I haven't accomplished much, but I do believe the only goal in life is to achieve a kind of equanimity and not about developing an identity. At death you slough off all your identities and what is then left? You lose your name, your family, your friends, your accomplishments, your control of your bowel movement and your very flesh, leaving behind even your attachment to earthly memories, by which I don't mean you necessarily forget this life but that those memories are recontextualized to a different level of awareness where those memories don't hold meaning and value anymore.  Robert, your advice may be practical to a 20 year old but at my age, it means very little. The true sign of aging is not the wrinkles on your face or the deterioration of the body, it is the experience of watching those you knew personally even intimately leave this life before you, one by one. If you live to your nineties, all the peers that supported your life goal is likely dead or simply don't care about such things anymore.  You come into the world in diapers and you will leave this world in one, unless it is somehow cut short. What life goal will carry you through to the very end? You can negotiate that death comes for us all, some sooner than others, and the trappings of identity only matters to those left behind, the deceased care not.

comment_text: Absolutely fascinating! Your explanations are spot on and this designated with me on so many levels, myself, my marriage, my children and my business. video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text: Fantastic interview!!  Some comments for what it's worth: 1) Envy: many, if not all, early human societies (and, arguably perhaps, still some today) operated on a system of "generalized reciprocity," which means that one gives something with no specific expectation for when the gift is returned nor does the returned gift have to be the same as the original one.  Malinowski's "pure gift" is one that entails no expectation of return.  In fact, a returned gift offends the giver, implying that one aims to cut the social tie to which the gift refers.  In such social systems, individual exceptionalism is also powerfully inhibited in favor of social unity.  So, something like winning a competition is viewed as anti-social, in a sense, and social mechanisms are in place that eliminate even the desire to do so.  Just thought this might be interesting for some.  2) Porn/love: I think/wonder whether the "sublime" is produced more from the synergy of otherwise distinct energies vs the "melting" of two into one?  Either way, in a competitive capitalist system, as with American culture, envy is a pronounced human experience (which, perhaps, leads to things like innovation) that may limit the trust (for lack of a better word) required to endure/overcome the inherent insecure experiences ("ego softening?") that accompany our encounters with the sublime/love?  Love the framing of love vs porn as enchantment vs disenchantment!  The "mechanizing" of sex by the porn industry, again, seems to cleanly align with an economic system in which everything is commodified and the primary drive is profit (i.e., to gain the advantage over another--negative reciprocity--which, of course, relates to envy).  Anyhoo...

comment_text:
@@chrisbenoit5044 for the people who don't get what you are writing 
 CTE – Chronic Traumatic Encephalopathy: A degenerative brain condition caused by repeated head trauma, often seen in athletes and military veterans.
TBI – Traumatic Brain Injury: A brain injury caused by a sudden impact, blow, or jolt to the head, which can lead to long-term cognitive and behavioral changes.
TPO – Temporary Protective Order: A legal order that restricts someone’s contact with another person due to concerns about safety, often issued in cases of domestic violence or threats.
BPD – Borderline Personality Disorder: A mental health condition characterized by emotional instability, impulsivity, difficulty in relationships, and, in some cases, intense anger or aggression.

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text: Yeah, he's not being completely truthful. Robert Greene knows what sells. Broad stroke statements like that everyone are narcicists and that there are multiple kinds of intelligence is using words so they can mean anything. Sure, you can look at athetic skill as intelligence. but modern science differentiates between TALENT & intelligence for a reason, and he's conflating the two. You can be talented at basketball because you have very long legs, that's talent not intelligence. Similarly being able to move fast & coordinated is not intelligence, it's talent. Intelligence is IQ, which is what makes a person able to learn any skill through pattern recognition & future prediction. The higher IQ, the faster a person is able to learn & excell at anything in life, that's intelligence. As far narcicism saying everyone is a narcicist because people have dark & egoitstic motives sometimes is too simplified. Narcicism is a diagnosis whih needs to fit certain critera, most people are not narcicists. Narcicists gaslight, they have a messiah complex where they think they know the best about everything, often times outside of their field of expertise as well, they get a trauma response and lash out once you see through them or when they get a crack in their worldview. They try to control other people, there are multiple checkboxes like this that narcicists check off. Normal people don't. Sure, a normal person might try to influence another person for their own gain, but they're not going to force it with lies & manipulation and gaslighting and other strategies typical for narcicism. So yeah idk.. when I was younger I used to look up to Robert Greene but as I've grown older I've started to see big cracks in many of his insights, they paint the world too black & white for me to want to follow along.

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text:
There are indeed many interesting things brought up, and Stephen has some interesting guests. 

However, his bringing up Steve Jobs and Elon Musk, time and time again…cause me to wonder. 
Yes, they have had incredible “focus” and achieved a lot by our western narrow L hemisphere brain idealization of “success”. However, their rigidity, and win at all costs, fixation on an end goal, with little ability to see where exceptions and context need to be factored in…have created grave consequences in their relationships. If you do not get the profound big picture, that relationships are everything (not merely a transactional tool, as Jobs and Musk mostly viewed relationships) then you are missing the most important point of life. 
Everything is about relationships. Our relationship to self, the world, others, and all the interconnectedness, the domino effect of all our thoughts and choices. 
If you take time/energy to focus on your special interests at the cost of relationships…you can end up with a profound deficit, a negative balance in the relationship “account”.

Not all that matters is measurable by metrics. You have to get this to truly understand the path to contentment and having the biggest impact in the world (positive impact). 

Also, of note, both Jobs and Musk were/are on the autism spectrum. Their brains are wired for incredible fixation, focus on detail, to the exclusion of almost everything else. Add to this, the disorder (developmental issues) of social, emotional, relational functioning. 
This sets them up to “succeed” in the areas they are in (more than most neurotypicals) but to almost invariably fail at relating well to others and building strong connections and relationships, beyond transactional ones. They don’t “get” the reciprocity, give/take, learning, evolution as a human, within the framework of relationships. 

Be so careful to not hyper-fixate on their high level achievements…without looking at the equation as a whole. You’re not seeing the high, high cost, deficits of their “success” if you look at it with such a limited view. 
Maybe pick different heroes?

video_title: We Are Making Dangerous, Lonely & Broken Men! - Manipulation Expert, Robert Greene! 48 Laws Of Power
comment_text:
Subject: A Little Love and a Little Feedback

Hey Steven Bartlett & Team,

Big fan here. Love the show, love your interviews, love that you make people feel like actual humans instead of soundbites. So, two quick suggestions—think of them as gentle nudges rather than rocks thrown at your podcasting window.

The “why aren’t more of you subscribed?” lament at the start – I get it. It’s baffling. It’s unjust. But leading with that feels a bit like starting a dinner party by scolding your guests for not RSVPing. Also, “this has always blown my mind a little bit” comes off as out of touch—plus, let’s be real, a guy with 9.59 million subscribers having a moan about not having more isn’t a great look. Instead, I’d encourage framing it as an invitation at the end: a heartfelt invitation to your non-subscribers to join this incredible community of subscribers and be part of your mission. It’s a call to action, not a plea for validation.

The previous guest question at the end – A very cool idea in theory, but in practice, it sometimes yanks us out of those beautifully natural endings you craft. Like watching the final scene of a great movie, then suddenly being quizzed on your favorite salad dressing. I remember this from your incredible episode with Dr. Lembke—it worked, but it also felt like a hard left turn. Maybe shift it toward the middle so it feels more like an interesting aside rather than an abrupt detour?

Anyway, you’re more incredible than you may realize, but it comes off better from showing, not telling.

Sincerely,
Someone who was once a straight-A student but after a series of misfortunes—including my mom dying of cancer and losing a job I loved because the founder pivoted—am now unemployed and struggling to get back on my feet. Your podcast is helping with that. That moment toward the end of the podcast with MrBeast was touching; cherish your moms and buy them more houses, all you thoughtful and charming entrepreneurs out there <3 

P.S. Not enough plebeians and peons give critical feedback to their superheroes, so you don’t need to come after me and my shitty little YouTube channel. Constructive feedback doesn’t always come top-down; it can be bottom-up, with humility. Also, if you’re not familiar with it, check out Lovemarks and how it relates to branding. I think you'd dig it. You all could rank how well you're doing at the following on a scale from 1-10, and discuss collectively how to increase anything that's a 7 or below:

Create Emotional Connections: Go beyond transactions; build stories around each guest that resonate deeply with the audience’s emotions, not just their intellect.
Cultivate Mystery: Leave some aspects of your brand and guests open-ended or intriguing, prompting curiosity and engagement.
Personalize the Experience: Tailor interactions, making each listener feel like a unique part of the Diary of a CEO community.
Develop a Signature Ritual: A recurring segment or phrase that creates familiarity and a sense of belonging, reinforcing loyalty.
Amplify the Dream: Align the show’s narrative with bigger, meaningful goals (e.g., purpose-driven entrepreneurship) to inspire listeners, making them feel part of a larger mission.
Humanize the Brand: Share more about your personal struggles and triumphs, making you and the show more relatable, thus deepening the emotional bond.
Encourage Participation: Let listeners feel like contributors, not just consumers—be it through feedback, questions, or joining the community via social media.
author: @WakeUpWithWake

comment_text: My upbringing was deeply religous, and I was taught from a young age that as a child of God, my life's purpose is not complicated, but very simple. It's to learn to be a good person who tries to leave the world a little better than i found it, to learn to love God and follow Jesus's example by serving my fellow man. I'm grateful for the fact that my purpose wasn't tied to my profession. No matter what twist or turn my career to, and it has taken many, my purpose hasn't changed. No matter what success you achieve in life, you can't take your riches with you and, save for a few truly exceptional people, your life and accomplishments will mostly be forgotten by nearly everyone within a decade or two. So stop worrying so much about what job you do to earn a living. Most any career can be rewarding enough if you find a good team to work with. Work to live, don't live to work. comment_text:
Great insights for young people. We have to listen to our gut, and how we resonate and react to things as he said. I remember dealing with a guy who was in my now present profession, when I was 17 and all I remember is that it was magical, and I couldn’t get enough but I didn’t have the sense to connect the dots at the time. Fortunately, there are a lot more resources available to us now than back then. But sometimes that also muddies the waters too. 

For the last 15+years kids have been so wrapped up dealing with their social media that they have not reached out to possible mentors who have been around the block a few times and know better what to expect and can provide better guidance. Assuming they are wise of course. I used to call it, the blind leading the blind generation. When one of them got into a lot of trouble or in over their head, all their friends would try to help them, but they had no clue either. And no connection with any mentors or even parents to help them. They just get totally overwhelmed.

Limiting beliefs are the biggest barrier  to happiness, much of the time.

comment_text:
“dialed-down or dialed-up version of themselves” Isn’t that an oxymoron? How can someone be a “version” of themselves but still the same? The concept of being “dialed up” or “dialed down” while also being different versions seems contradictory.

Additionally, what you’re suggesting is not entirely accurate when it comes to personality disorders. People with personality disorders, such as NPD, exhibit rigid and inflexible behaviors, making them more likely to present the same way across different environments. This lack of flexibility is why pervasiveness is a key criterion in diagnosing personality disorders.

While some people might find certain environments like a job or friendship stress free and therefore not exhibit toxic responses, unhealthy narcissism tends to be rigid and inflexible. As a result, these traits usually manifest regardless of the context.

Everyone who desires the external world to reflect their image, which is the beliefs and ideals that define their ego or self-identity, is a narcissist to some extent. Narcissistic traits are on a spectrum. The extreme is NPD.

comment_text: I have always known that I would be working with children and families and when I couldn’t do that I was very unhappy. All the things just aligned for me. My present employment I did not apply to this position. They found me on Indeed and I didn’t realize it until I was accepting the offer and I was working in the state next to me 😂 it is close but still another state. And here I am 14 months later and I am successful, highly trained and sought after for the tough cases. As well as, helping women to find the inner strength to get out of poverty and be independent, recognize stress triggers, and be able to become what they desire to be, and then they become the best parents. I have the ability to see who can do it and who can’t find that alignment from their situation. And I am a contractor so it allows me the flexibility I need as a person living with a rare lymphoma and at 62. I mean life is what we make it and I believe there is a predestination to this life. And we either attain that or we live in misery. And not everyone has a predestination. Their life is to maybe just be someone that can farm, or be a mother, and if you are in alignment then you feel happy with the life you are in. If you aren’t happy then you are not in alignment and will have to find the alignment through trial and error. My path was hijacked by abusive parenting, abandonment, and still, I found my alignment because situations were constantly presented to me. I just had to make the choices. It has been a journey, this life.
